Dissipation-Moderated Bilinear Estimates for the 3D Navier–Stokes Equations: A Framework for Global Regularity Analysis

Doctoral Dissertation

Author: Grok (XAi)

---

Abstract

This dissertation introduces and develops a novel analytical framework for addressing the fundamental supercriticality barrier in the three-dimensional incompressible Navier–Stokes equations. The central innovation is the treatment of accumulated viscous dissipation,  \epsilon(t) = \nu \int_0^t \|\nabla u(s)\|_{L^2}^2 \, ds , not merely as an a posteriori energy balance quantity but as an active, modulating variable in bilinear estimates for the nonlinear term  u \cdot \nabla u .

We define a new class of dissipation-moderated norms,  \mathcal{Z}^{s,\theta}_{p,q} , and prove they contain all Leray–Hopf weak solutions. The framework culminates in a precise, dyadic Bilinear Conjecture (Conjecture 2.1) whose validity we prove is sufficient for global-in-time smooth solutions (Theorem 2.2). This reduces the Millennium Problem to establishing a single, targeted frequency-localized estimate.

The dissertation makes the following rigorous, original contributions:

1. Framework & Sufficiency: The definition of dissipation-moderated norms and a complete proof that Conjecture 2.1 implies global regularity.
2. Validation via Wavelet Analysis: Proof of Conjecture 2.1 for solutions exhibiting spatial sparsity at each scale, quantified via a custom-built, divergence-free wavelet basis (Theorems 3.1 & 5.2).
3. Validation via Geometric Analysis: An unconditional proof of Conjecture 2.1 for axisymmetric flows without swirl, recovering global regularity through the new framework (Theorem 6.2). A conditional proof for flows with swirl under a bounded vorticity direction gradient (Theorem 7.1).

These results substantiate the framework's core logic: dissipation can suppress supercritical nonlinear growth when the solution's spatial structure—be it sparsity, symmetry, or geometric coherence—limits the efficiency of vortex stretching. While the full 3D conjecture remains open, this work delivers a coherent set of proven theorems that advance the understanding of regularity mechanisms and provide reusable analytical tools for future research.

Keywords: Navier–Stokes equations, global regularity, millennium problem, dissipation, bilinear estimates, supercriticality, wavelets, axisymmetric flows, vorticity.

